Ruoyu Wu

2023-06-30

Fig. 1

Summary of 11 fungal spore metrics. The annotation of 11 fungal spore metrics (A). Orange indicates metrics defined in ecological approach, while dark red indicates metrics defined in public health approach. Each box represents the interquartile range (IQR) of each metric, with the median value indicated by the line inside. Whiskers extend to the minimum and maximum values within 1.5 times the IQR, while points beyond the whiskers are considered outliers. Phenology metrics are presented in Day of Year (DOY) format (C), while magnitude metrics are displayed in a natural logarithm-transformed scale (B) (D).

Fig. 2

Fungal spore calendar for 10 sample stations. Displayed is the daily long-term mean of fungal spore concentration, 2003-2022. Stations showing variability in seasonality are sorted by longitude (A). Stations showing variability in magnitude are sorted by long-term mean of annual precipitation (mm) (B). Darker colors indicate higher concentrations, while missing data are represented in white.

Fig. 3

Temporal trends of 8 fungal spore metrics across all the stations (continental level). Predicted slope from linear mixed effects models across stations of year against the sos (A), sas (B), los (C), las (D), amplitude (E), peak (F), AIn (G), and ASIn (H). Top row presents metrics defined in ecological method, while bottom row shows metrics defined in public health way. Points are individual years at individual stations. Solid lines indicate significant slope, while dashed lines indicate non-significant slope. Colorful lines are station-level trends. Point/line colors are stations. Shaded areas indicate the 95% CI of the fixed effect. Concentration metrics are transformed using the natural logarithm.

Fig. 4

Temporal trends of 3 fungal spore metrics (individual station level) and their correlation with climate change. Linear trends over individual stations of the sas (A), peak (D), and AIn (F) and their significant correlation with climate change: advanced sas influenced by warming (B) and wetting (C), and dryings impacts on decreased peak (E) and AIn (G). Warm colors indicate increasing magnitude or earlier season and circle size is proportional to the years of data at each station. Crossed circles show the significance. Magnitude metrics are transformed using the natural logarithm.
